    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  The neutralizing monoclonal antibody combination of tixagevimab/cilgavimab has been shown to reduce the risk of SARS-CoV-2 infection in unvaccinated individuals during the Alpha (B.1.1.7) and Delta (B.1.617.2) waves. However, data on efficacy and safety of tixagevimab/cilgavimab in vaccinated solid organ transplant recipients during the Omicron wave is limited. To address this, we conducted a retrospective cohort study comparing 222 solid organ transplant recipients who received tixagevimab/cilgavimab for pre-exposure prophylaxis and 222 age-matched vaccinated solid organ transplant recipients who did not receive tixagevimab/cilgavimab. Subjects were followed for a mean of 67 \u00b1 18 days. Kaplan-Meier estimates of the 60-day incidence of breakthrough infection were 1.8% in the tixagevimab/cilgavimab group and 4.7% in the control group (\n                  <jats:italic>P</jats:italic>\n                  = 0.045). Adverse events were uncommon, occurring in 4% of our cohort and most were mild. There was no significant change in serum creatinine or liver chemistries in kidney and liver transplant recipients respectively. In conclusion, we found that tixagevimab/cilgavimab use is safe and associated with a lower risk of breakthrough SARS-CoV-2 infection in vaccinated solid organ transplant recipients during the Omicron wave.\n                </jats:p>",
